      "purposeInStoryline": "This lesson is the pivot of the unit — students have spent three lessons building the tools (recognising, expanding, factorising) and now finally use those tools to fully solve the Harambee hall problem and answer the committee's original question. The two solutions w equals 10 and w equals negative 12 create a productive cognitive conflict that anchors the big idea: mathematics gives you answers, but community wisdom and physical reasoning tell you which answer to use.",
